I18n violations related to honorific or personal titles often occur when an application or website assumes that all users have the same title or do not consider different cultural norms related to titles. Here is an example in Java:


```java
public class User {
 private String firstName;
 private String lastName;
 private String title;

 public User(String firstName, String lastName, String title) {
 this.firstName = firstName;
 this.lastName = lastName;
 this.title = title;
 }

 public String getFullNameWithTitle() {
 return title + " " + firstName + " " + lastName;
 }
}
```
In the above example, the `User` class has a `title` field, which assumes that all users have the same title. This can be problematic in countries where titles vary based on factors such as gender, age, profession, and social status. It can also be an issue in cultures where using titles is not common practice.

To make this code I18n compliant, we can modify the `User` class to allow for different titles based on the user's cultural norms. One way to do this is by using a localized `ResourceBundle` to get the appropriate title based on the user's locale. Here is an updated version of the `User` class:


```java
import java.util.Locale;
import java.util.ResourceBundle;

public class User {
 private String firstName;
 private String lastName;
 private Locale locale;

 public User(String firstName, String lastName, Locale locale) {
 this.firstName = firstName;
 this.lastName = lastName;
 this.locale = locale;
 }

 public String getFullNameWithTitle() {
 ResourceBundle titles = ResourceBundle.getBundle("titles", locale);
 String title = titles.getString("title");
 return title + " " + firstName + " " + lastName;
 }
}
```
In this updated version of the `User` class, we have removed the `title` field and replaced it with a `locale` field. We then use this locale to get the appropriate title from a `ResourceBundle`. The `ResourceBundle` contains key-value pairs for each title based on the user's locale. For example, a `titles.properties` file for users in Japan might contain the following:


```makefile
title=様
```
And a `titles.properties` file for users in the United States might contain the following:


```makefile
title=Mr./Ms.
```
By using a `ResourceBundle` and getting the appropriate title based on the user's locale, we ensure that our application or website is more inclusive and respects different cultural norms related to honorifics and personal titles.

